fts policy in the direction of majority opinion. More important, she also shows that presidents rarely cater to the mass citizenry unless they already agree with the public's preferred course of action. With contemporary politics so connected to the pulse of the American people, Who Leads Whom? offers much-needed insight into how public opinion actually works in our democratic process. Integrating perspectives from presidential studies, legislative politics, public opinion, and rational choice theory, this theoretical and empirical inquiry will appeal to a wide range of scholars of American political processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxDecision making. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aleadership, politics, public opinion, power, political science, presidency, president, executive, government, policy, legislation, congress, clinton, eisenhower, majority, rational choice theory, decision making, pandering, nonfiction, history, popularity, pr, conflict resolution, utility, citizenry, electorate, voters, constituency.1 aShotts, With, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226092492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226092492/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles